Transfer of Thermal Energy

Welcome to the Thermal Lab!

Principle of Conduction

Conduction is the main method of thermal energy transfer in solids. It involves the transfer of kinetic energy between adjacent particles. The particles themselves do not move from their positions.

How does conduction work in non-metals?
When one end of a solid is heated, the atoms gain kinetic energy and vibrate more. They bump into their neighbours, transferring this vibrational energy along the solid from the hot end to the cold end.
Why are metals special?
Metals are excellent thermal conductors because they have free electrons. These electrons gain kinetic energy at the hot end and move quickly through the metal, colliding with other atoms and transferring energy much faster than vibrations alone. This is called electron diffusion.

Conductors & Insulators

Good Conductors: Materials that transfer heat easily (e.g., metals like copper, aluminium).

Bad Conductors (Insulators): Materials that do not transfer heat well (e.g., wool, plastic, wood, gases, liquids).

Experiment: Comparing Conductors

A simple experiment involves a rod made of a conductor (like copper) coated in wax. Ball bearings are stuck to the wax. When one end is heated, the wax melts and the ball bearings drop off in sequence from the hot end to the cold end, demonstrating the transfer of heat.

(Refer to the diagram of the metal rod experiment).

Experiment: Tiles vs. Textiles

If you stand with one bare foot on a tile floor and the other on a rug in the same room, the tile feels colder. This is because the tile is a good conductor and quickly transfers heat away from your foot. The rug is an insulator and transfers heat slowly, so it feels warmer, even though both are at the same room temperature.

Conduction Quiz

Principle of Convection

Convection is the main way thermal energy is transferred through fluids (liquids and gases). It happens when the particles themselves move, carrying thermal energy with them. This movement is called a convection current.

How Convection Currents Work

  1. A region of the fluid is heated.
  2. The particles gain energy, move faster, and spread apart. The fluid expands and becomes less dense.
  3. This less dense, hot fluid rises.
  4. Cooler, denser fluid from above sinks to take its place.
  5. This cooler fluid is then heated, and the cycle repeats.
Everyday Examples
  • Kettle: The heating element is at the bottom. It heats the water, which rises, and cooler water sinks to be heated, creating a current.
  • Room Heater: Heaters are placed on the floor to heat the air, which then rises and circulates around the room.

Convection Quiz

Principle of Radiation

All objects above absolute zero emit and absorb thermal energy via infrared (IR) radiation. This is a type of electromagnetic wave and does not require a medium (particles) to travel. This is how we feel the Sun's heat through the vacuum of space.

Surface Properties: Emitters

Black & Dull Surfaces: Are good emitters of IR radiation.

White & Shiny Surfaces: Are poor emitters of IR radiation.

Surface Properties: Absorbers & Reflectors

Black & Dull Surfaces: Are good absorbers of IR radiation.

White & Shiny Surfaces: Are poor absorbers (and good reflectors) of IR radiation.

Exam Quick-Fact
A good absorber is also a good emitter. A poor absorber (good reflector) is also a poor emitter. The properties go hand-in-hand.

Experiment: Leslie's Cube

A Leslie's cube is a hollow metal cube with four different surfaces (e.g., matt black, gloss white, shiny silver, dull copper). It's filled with hot water. An infrared detector shows that the matt black surface emits the most radiation, while the shiny silver surface emits the least.

(Refer to the diagram of the Leslie's cube experiment).

Radiation Quiz

Application: The Vacuum Flask

A vacuum flask (or thermos) is designed to minimise heat transfer by all three methods to keep hot liquids hot and cold liquids cold.

  • Conduction/Convection: The vacuum between the two walls prevents heat transfer by conduction and convection, as there are almost no particles. The plastic cap is an insulator and reduces heat loss through the opening.
  • Radiation: The walls are silvered and shiny. This makes them poor emitters and poor absorbers (good reflectors) of infrared radiation, reflecting thermal energy back into the hot liquid (or away from the cold liquid).

(Refer to the diagram of a vacuum flask).

The Greenhouse Effect

The Sun emits short-wavelength radiation that passes through the Earth's atmosphere. The Earth absorbs this, warms up, and emits longer-wavelength IR radiation. Greenhouse gases (like CO‚ÇÇ) absorb this outgoing IR radiation, trapping the thermal energy and keeping the Earth warm.

Combined Transfers: A Fire

A wood fire in a room transfers heat in all three ways:

  • Radiation: The fire emits IR radiation, which travels directly to nearby objects and people.
  • Convection: The air above the fire is heated, becomes less dense, and rises, creating a convection current that circulates heat around the room.
  • Conduction: The floor beneath the fire can be heated by conduction.
